The Canadian Press


OTTAWA -- The Liberal government says it will make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell marijuana in Canada.

Health Minister Jane Philpott announced Wednesday the government will make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell marijuana in Canada.

Philpott said the government is also looking to make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell medical marijuana.

Philpott said Wednesday the government is also looking to make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell medical marijuana. (Adrian Wyld/Canadian Press)

"We want to make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell medical marijuana," Philpott told reporters.

"We're also looking to make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell recreational marijuana."

Philpott said the government will make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell recreational marijuana, which is already legal in Canada.

She said the government is also looking to make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell medical marijuana, which is already legal in Canada. (Adrian Wyld/Canadian Press)

Philpott said the government is also looking to make it easier for Canadians to buy and sell medical marijuana, which is already legal in Canada.
Noun: One who opposes the government's policy

Etymology: From the French nuit, from the Latin nunc, literally 'to oppose', from nomere 'against, oppose' + corpus 'object' (also nauta 'object').

What does this say about our politics?

The word Nuit seems to suggest something about the attitudes of our leaders – it may mean that they oppose government policy, or that they don't approve of it. However, it also seems to refer to our leaders' stance regarding certain specific aspects of the government policy.

For example, "The mayor of Paris says that he thinks there should be no change in the law." This is a different stance from that of the Prime Minister, whose words "there is no question of change" imply that this is the policy he supports.

The mayor's remarks do not necessarily mean that he has support from the leadership – it could simply mean that he doesn't agree with the way the policy is being pursued.

However, it is difficult to be sure about this for two reasons.

First, it could be that the leaders are aware of the possibility that the policy is not working as intended.

For example,
