S. 645, a bill to amend the United States Code to extend the life of the National Security Act, includes an extension of the authority for the President to waive section 904(f) of the Act of September 30, 1972. This is not a partisan issue. Many Members of Congress have strong feelings on the issue of Section 904(f), and we have tried to be fair in allowing the President to waive the statutory requirement for such an extension.  The extension of section 904(f) to permit the President to waive this section was signed into law in 1975. A decade ago, the American Legion and the American Trade Association strongly urged the administration to extend the statutory provision. Congress has finally passed the bill.  It is instructive to look at the history of section 904(f) before passing it. Section 904(f) was adopted at the close of the Korean war. The provision was intended to allow the President to postpone, at the discretion of the Secretary of the Treasury, the acquisition of U.S. national defense articles until the conclusion of the United Nations Conference on Security Council Resolutions [UNSCR] of 1947. It was not meant as a blank check to the President, the President, in any event
